Here's the setup:

```csharp
// MauiProgram.cs
public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

        // One HttpClient + DataService for the entire app lifetime
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<HttpClient>();
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

        // Fresh ViewModel per navigation to avoid stale state
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // Fresh page per navigation so UI binds to fresh ViewModel
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Why each lifetime:**

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `HttpClient` | **Singleton** | Reusing one instance avoids socket exhaustion. Thread-safe by design. |
| `IDataService` | **Singleton** | Wraps `HttpClient`, holds no per-user state — one instance is enough and lets you add caching easily. |
| `MainViewModel` / `DetailViewModel` | **Transient** | Each navigation gets a fresh VM, preventing stale data or leftover state from a previous visit. |
| `MainPage` / `DetailPage` | **Transient** | Pages pair 1:1 with their ViewModel. A fresh page binds to a fresh VM on every navigation. |

**Key rule of thumb:** services that are stateless or manage shared resources → **Singleton**. UI-bound objects that carry per-screen state → **Transient**. Use **Scoped** only if you have a well-defined scope (e.g., a multi-step wizard sharing state across sub-pages).
